body:
```SystemVerilog
module top;
	parameter ENABLE = 1;
	if (ENABLE) begin : blk
		wire [7:0] w;
	end
	wire [7:0] x;
	wire [$bits(blk.w)-1:0] y;
	wire [$bits(x)-1:0] z;
	initial begin
		$display("blk.w: %b (%0d bits)", blk.w, $bits(blk.w));
		$display("x: %b (%0d bits)", x, $bits(x));
		$display("y: %b (%0d bits)", y, $bits(y));
		$display("z: %b (%0d bits)", z, $bits(z));
	end
endmodule
```

When simulating the above test case, most tools produce:
```
blk.w: zzzzzzzz (8 bits)
x: zzzzzzzz (8 bits)
y: zzzzzzzz (8 bits)
z: zzzzzzzz (8 bits)
```

However, iverilog (both version 11.0 and the latest master) produces:
```
blk.w: zzzzzzzz (8 bits)
x: zzzzzzzz (8 bits)
y: xx (0 bits)
z: zzzzzzzz (8 bits)
```
Notice that `$bits(blk.w)` correctly evaluates to `8` in the `$display` call, but not in the declaration of `y`.

